abstract: Mr. Weisselberg has referred to himself as President Trump’s “eyes and ears” at the Trump Organization. He was incriminated by Michael Cohen in testimony on Wednesday.

abstract: With the primary race already historically crowded, some analysts say the old rules about when to announce no longer matter.
snippet: With the primary race already historically crowded, some analysts say the old rules about when to announce no longer matter.
lead_paragraph: The country is 337 days away from the Iowa caucuses and 611 days from the general election for president. But that’s not stopping Democrats from debating the politics of entering the race really, really early or just, well, plain old-fashioned early.

headline_main: DealBook Briefing: Cohen Trashes Trump’s Business Image

abstract: The president’s former lawyer, Michael Cohen, testified that Donald Trump presented documents to Deutsche Bank that “inflated” the value of his assets.
snippet: The president’s former lawyer, Michael Cohen, testified that Donald Trump presented documents to Deutsche Bank that “inflated” the value of his assets.
lead_paragraph: In early 2014, Donald J. Trump approached his personal bankers at Deutsche Bank to sound them out about potentially lending him money to buy the Buffalo Bills. He provided the bankers with a collection of bare-bones personal financial statements.

abstract: The House voted Wednesday to require background checks for all gun purchasers, the first major expansion of gun control laws in over two decades.
snippet: The House voted Wednesday to require background checks for all gun purchasers, the first major expansion of gun control laws in over two decades.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The House voted on Wednesday to require background checks for all gun purchasers, including those at gun shows and on the internet — the first significant gun control bill to clear the chamber in a quarter of a century.

headline_print_headline: With Big Thoughts, Her Business Blooms

abstract: The Associated Press and the White House Correspondents’ Association denounced the restriction on journalists’ access to a meeting between the president and North Korea’s autocratic leader.
snippet: The Associated Press and the White House Correspondents’ Association denounced the restriction on journalists’ access to a meeting between the president and North Korea’s autocratic leader.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The White House on Wednesday barred four American journalists from covering President Trump’s dinner with the North Korean leader, Kim Jong-un, in Hanoi, Vietnam, after two of the reporters called out questions to Mr. Trump at an earlier appearance.
